"1391–Male":"1391–Overleden","1414–Male":"1414–Overleden","1418–Male":"1418–Overleden","1392–Female":"1392–Overleden","1414":"1414","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1391":"1391","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1392–":"1392–Deceased","1391–Male":"1391–Deceased","1414–Male":"1414–Deceased","1418–Male":"1418–Deceased","1392–Female":"1392–Deceased","1414":"1414","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1391":"1391","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Butler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a word that originally denoted a wine steward, usually the chief servant of a medieval household, from Norman French <i>butuiller</i> (Old French <i>bouteillier</i>, Latin <i>buticularius</i>, from <i>buticula</i> ‘bottle’). In the large households of royalty and the most powerful nobility, the title came to denote an officer of high rank and responsibility, only nominally concerned with the supply of wine, if at all. As well as being widespread in England, this is also the surname of an important Irish family, descended from Theobald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel Butler was born in 1392, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John Trye."},"et":{"1392–":"1392–Surnud","1391–Male":"1391–Surnud","1414–Male":"1414–Surnud","1418–Male":"1418–Surnud","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1414":"1414","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1391":"1391","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1392–":"1392–Kuollut","1391–Male":"1391–Kuollut","1414–Male":"1414–Kuollut","1418–Male":"1418–Kuollut","1392–Female":"1392–Kuollut","1414":"1414","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1391":"1391","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdis